==Old English==

===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*petwōr'', from Indo-European ''*kwetwōr'' ‘four’.  Cognate with Old High German [[fior]] (German [[vier]]), Old Saxon [[fiuwar]] (Dutch [[vier]]), Old Norse ''fjórir'', Gothic [[𐍆𐌹𐌳𐍅𐍉𐍂]].  The IE root was also the source of Old Slavic ''četyre'' (Russian [[четыре]]), Old Irish [[cethair]], Greek [[τέσσαρες]], Latin [[quattuor]].

